Chapter 4: Ethical Constraints as Invariant Sets

We now translate ethical principles into mathematical objects.

4.1 Consent Set

Define the consent set \mathcal{U}_{\text{consent}}(\mathbf{x}) \subseteq \mathbb{R}^p as the set of intervention intensities the user permits when in state \mathbf{x}. This set is user‑configurable (e.g., via a digital interface) and must satisfy:

· 0 \in \mathcal{U}_{\text{consent}}(\mathbf{x}) for all \mathbf{x} (non‑intervention is always allowed).
· \mathcal{U}_{\text{consent}}(\mathbf{x}) is compact and convex (for technical convenience).
· The user may update \mathcal{U}_{\text{consent}}(\mathbf{x}) at any time; we model this as a switching signal.

4.2 Fairness Constraints

To prevent demographic bias, we add a demographic parity constraint: for any demographic group d, the intervention distribution should be independent of d given the state. In the CMDP formulation, this is enforced as

\mathbb{E}[\mathbf{u} \mid \mathbf{x}, d] = \mathbb{E}[\mathbf{u} \mid \mathbf{x}], \quad \forall d.

This is a linear constraint on the policy, compatible with CMDP methods.

4.3 Safe Set and Controlled Invariance

The safe set \mathcal{S} is defined as the set of states from which there exists a control \mathbf{u} \in \mathcal{U}_{\text{consent}}(\mathbf{x}) such that the state remains within \mathcal{S} for all future time under the worst‑case disturbance. Using viability theory, we characterize \mathcal{S} as the largest controlled invariant set contained in the region where the ethical constraints are satisfied.

Lemma 4.1 (Reversibility). Because 0 \in \mathcal{U}_{\text{consent}}(\mathbf{x}) for every \mathbf{x}, the uncontrolled system (with \mathbf{u}=0) is always feasible. Therefore, if the system reaches a state where the user withdraws consent, they can simply set \mathbf{u}=0 and the system evolves autonomously, ensuring reversibility.

