Chapter 7: System Architecture and Implementation (Theoretical)

We now outline the theoretical architecture that implements the above control scheme. The description remains platform‑agnostic and focuses on functional modules.

7.1 Block Diagram

The closed‑loop consists of:

1. Observation module: Collects raw signals (EEG, skin conductance, behavioral logs) and maps them to the observation vector \mathbf{y}_t.
2. State estimator: Produces \hat{\mathbf{x}}_t using a filter (e.g., extended Kalman filter) that propagates uncertainty and ensures \|\hat{\mathbf{x}}_t - \mathbf{x}_t\| \le \delta.
3. Policy optimizer: Computes a candidate control \mathbf{u}_{\text{RL}} that aims to maximize the multi‑objective reward while respecting constraints. In theory, this can be a safe RL algorithm that enforces constraints via Lagrangian methods.
4. Ethical constraint enforcer: Projects \mathbf{u}_{\text{RL}} onto the admissible set \mathcal{U}_{\text{consent}}(\hat{\mathbf{x}}_t) and applies the fading factor \kappa(V(\hat{\mathbf{x}}_t)).
5. Intervention generator: Delivers the actual neurofeedback (e.g., visual cues, auditory tones) with intensity scaled by \mathbf{u}_t.
6. Feedback integration: Updates the model parameters of the dynamics (e.g., learning the user’s specific \mathbf{f} and \mathbf{g}) slowly.

7.2 Theoretical Guarantees

Given the assumptions of Theorem 6.1, any implementation that provides a control law satisfying the same CLF condition and constraint satisfaction will inherit the stability and convergence properties. The policy optimizer can be designed using primal‑dual safe RL, with convergence guarantees from the literature [e.g., Chow et al. 2017].

