Chapter 8: Discussion and Limitations

We acknowledge several limitations, which also point to future research directions.

8.1 Mathematical Limitations

· The existence of a smooth CLF is assumed; for general nonlinear systems, constructing such a function is non‑trivial. In practice, one may approximate it via sum‑of‑squares programming or learning.
· The dimension n of the state is finite; scaling to very high dimensions (e.g., whole‑brain connectivity) may require dimensionality reduction.
· The disturbance bound D is assumed known; adaptive disturbance estimation could be integrated.

8.2 Ethical and Legal Limitations

· The fairness constraint (demographic parity) is a simplified notion; more sophisticated fairness criteria may be required.
· Coercive voluntariness remains a philosophical challenge even with our consent set; the system’s use must be accompanied by independent oversight.
· Neural data rights are evolving; the architecture should be designed to comply with emerging regulations (e.g., UNESCO’s neuroethics framework).

8.3 Practical Considerations

· Real‑world sensor noise and variability may exceed the assumed boundedness.
· User adherence to the intervention protocol cannot be guaranteed; the model assumes the user does not tamper with the feedback.
· The separation of timescales (fast control, slow learning) may break if the brain’s plasticity is fast; this would require a more sophisticated adaptive control analysis.

